This code creates a visual comparison of bubble sort, quick sort, and merge sort. Each algorithm is run on the same randomized data, and the step count for each algorithm is displayed. The time complexities of each algorithm are also shown.

**Why Bubble Sort is Not the Best:**
Bubble sort has a worst-case and average time complexity of O(n^2), which makes it impractical for large data sets. Quick sort and merge sort, on the other hand, have average time complexities of O(n log n), making them much more efficient for large data sets.

**When to Use Bubble Sort:**
While bubble sort is not suitable for large data sets, it can be useful for small data sets or educational purposes. Its simplicity makes it easy to understand and implement.

**When to Use Quick Sort and Merge Sort:**
Quick sort and merge sort are suitable for large data sets and are widely used in many applications. Quick sort is generally faster than merge sort, but merge sort has a guaranteed time complexity of O(n log n), making it a better choice when predictability is important.

