| Quick Sort   | O(n log n)      | O(log n)        |

The performance gap between bubble sort and the other two algorithms (merge sort and quick sort) is significant. Bubble sort has a time complexity of O(n^2), which makes it inefficient for large datasets. Merge sort and quick sort have average-case time complexities of O(n log n), which is much better than bubble sort. 

In general, merge sort and quick sort are preferred over bubble sort for most use cases. However, the choice of sorting algorithm ultimately depends on the specific requirements and constraints of the problem.

