<body>

<h1>Buggy Version</h1>
<div class="example">
  <button id="buggy-inc">Increment</button>
  <button id="buggy-dec">Decrement</button>
  <span id="buggy-count">Count: 0</span>
</div>

<h1>Fixed Version</h1>
<div class="example">
  <button id="fixed-inc">Increment</button>
  <button id="fixed-dec">Decrement</button>
  <span id="fixed-count">Count: 0</span>
</div>

<script>
  // Buggy Version
  let buggyCount = 0;
  document.getElementById('buggy-inc').addEventListener('click', () => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      const currentCount = buggyCount;
      buggyCount = currentCount + 1;
      document.getElementById('buggy-count').textContent = `Count: ${buggyCount}`;
    }, 10);
  });
  document.getElementById('buggy-dec').addEventListener('click', () => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      const currentCount = buggyCount;
      buggyCount = currentCount - 1;
      document.getElementById('buggy-count').textContent = `Count: ${buggyCount}`;
    }, 10);
  });

  // Fixed Version
  let fixedCount = 0;
  let pendingUpdate = false;
  document.getElementById('fixed-inc').addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (pendingUpdate) return;
    pendingUpdate = true;
    setTimeout(() => {
      fixedCount++;
      document.getElementById('fixed-count').textContent = `Count: ${fixedCount}`;
      pendingUpdate = false;
    }, 10);
  });
  document.getElementById('fixed-dec').addEventListener('click', () => {
    if (pendingUpdate) return;
    pendingUpdate = true;
    setTimeout(() => {
      fixedCount--;
      document.getElementById('fixed-count').textContent = `Count: ${fixedCount}`;
      pendingUpdate = false;
    }, 10);
  });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

**Why the buggy version breaks:**

The buggy version uses `setTimeout` to simulate an asynchronous operation. When the "Increment" or "Decrement" button is clicked, it reads the current count, increments or decrements it, and then writes the new count back to the shared state.

The problem arises when multiple clicks are made in rapid succession. The `setTimeout` function does not guarantee that the callback will be executed immediately; instead, it schedules the callback to be executed after a certain delay.

If multiple clicks are made before the previous callback has a chance to execute, the shared state `buggyCount` is read multiple times, and each callback modifies the same initial value. This results in lost updates, causing the count to become incorrect.

**How the fixed version works:**

The fixed version uses a `pendingUpdate` flag to prevent multiple updates from being scheduled simultaneously. When a click event is received, it checks the `pendingUpdate` flag. If it's already `true`, the new click event is ignored. Otherwise, it sets `pendingUpdate` to `true`, schedules the update using `setTimeout`, and then sets `pendingUpdate` back to `false` when the update is complete.

By preventing concurrent updates, the fixed version ensures that the shared state `fixedCount` is updated correctly, even under rapid asynchronous clicks.

